  "text": "Inferring dispersal from isolation-by-distance (IBD) patterns is one approach that seems to 52 stand out by its (relatively) wide applicability. The dynamics of genetic variation in populations along a gradient of spatial proximity were first formalized by Wright (1943) , Malécot (1949) , and Kimura & 54 Weiss (1964) . These and following IBD theoretical developments have set ground for several inference methods that aim at estimating dispersal from genetic data (reviewed in Guillot et al. 56 2009). We focus here on the method proposed by [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , which uses a regression of genetic distances on geographic distances among pairs of samples to infer the product Dσ 2 , where D 58 is the effective density and σ 2 is the mean squared parent-offspring distance. If D can be independently estimated then σ 2 gives a synthetic descriptor of dispersal that can be compared 60 across populations or species (e.g. Pinsky et al. 2010 ; see also Vekemans & Hardy 2004 using a related approach), and possibly compared with field-based estimates (e.g. [CITATION_3] ). The 62 product Dσ 2 itself is also of interest as it informs us on the increase of differentiation with distance.",
